There is a ‘ y ‘ shaped hairline crack at the back of the action inletting, top of wrist. This does not appear to extend into the mass of the stock, but a part of it can be seen inside the inletting. A quick sanding and re-finishing would probably hide this flaw, but that wouldn’t be honest, would it? The globe front site is missing its knurled retaining nut that holds the inserts in place and the insert in place is homemade. It is retained by a piece of plastic that is a slip fit. Believe it or not this cobbled-up solution seems to work quite well (and could easily be improved – and kits of inserts are available inexpensively from several sources such as Brownells). I may have another, complete Brno globe front around here somewhere, and if I find it the price for the rifle will be adjusted upward accordingly.\ More pics available on request. The trigger comes from the factory with a 24 newtons (5.5 lbf) single-action pull, and is capable of both single-action and double-action. However, this trigger has been adjusted by profession gunsmith Buckhorn Firearms, Idaho and, now reads single-action 3.5 lb on my Timmey Trigger gauge. In single-action position, making for a very short trigger pull, with minimal take-up. The double-action pull is longer and much heavier. Like many Sig’s it has a de-cocking lever; using the de-cocking lever in order for the round to discharge, the full double-action pull would have to be completed, which allows for the pistol to be carried reasonably safely with a round chambered. The sights are of the traditional SIG design and configuration, with a dot on the front sight and a rectangle on the rear sight. $475 for the entire package.

postcontent:
Brand new in box Keltec Sub 2000 chambered in .40 SW. takes Glock magazines and comes with one 15 round magazine. 

TECHNICAL SPECS

Operating System	Blowback
Caliber	9mm Luger or 40 cal. S&W
Capacity	Varies by magazine

Accessory Mount

Length

13.25in / 14.5in
Grip Width	1.25in
Max Height	7 in
Weight (Unloaded, no mag)	4.25lbs
Barrel Threads (.40 cal.)	9/16"-24

DESCRIPTION

The SUB-2000™ is a semi-automatic rifle chambered for the 9mm Luger or the .40 cal. S&W cartridge. Different versions of the SUB-2000™ rifle will accept most double column handgun magazines (see list below).  By rotating the barrel upwards and back, the SUB-2000™ rifle can instantly be reduced to a size of 16.25 x 7 inches for ease of storage.

The polymer of the weapon is made of an impact modified glass reinforced Zytel.  Two integrated Picatinny rails come standard on the SUB-2000™ forend for mounting compatible accessories.  The forend also includes five mounting slots per side, configured for various M-LOK™ accessories. 

The stock can be adjusted to three different positions for shooter's comfort.  Each position adds approximately 5/8 of an inch to the overall length of the weapon, with a total extension of 1.25 inches in the further rearward position.  The stock includes a single point sling loop attachment, a slot for adding a nylon sling loop (1.25" wide is ideal), and a Picatinny rail on the bottom for adding small accessories. 

The SUB-2000™ features a push-bolt safety located behind the trigger on the grip assembly.  The bolt can be locked in the rear position by cycling the bolt to the rear and rotating the operating handle up into the cutout on the receiver.  The rear sight is of aperture type and the AR style front sight can be adjusted for windage and elevation. 

The thread protector on the SUB-2000™ is removable, if the shooter desires to replace the thread protector with a compatible accessory for the 1/2"-28 threads (9mm model) or 9/16"-24 threads (.40 cal S&W).  The SUB-2000™ can easily be disassembled for cleaning or inspection without tools.

The .40 SUB-2000™ can be configured in the following magazine types: GLK22. 

Prices is firm at $475. Please don't offer trades. 

Thanks for looking

Dale

title: For Sale:  Pre-Ban H&K Heckler & Koch G3 Hk-91
postcontent:
Manufactured by Heckler and Koch in 1981 ('IB' coded receiver), this is the semi-automatic version of the G3 rifle. Chambered for 7.62x51 NATO (.308). Those of you who are familiar with the Hk-91 already know that the manufacturing quality, reliability, and accuracy of these German-produced rifles is unmatched. A ban on the import of these rifles took effect in 1989, so whatever made it into the U.S. prior to that is what's available on the market. This is one of the 48,817 Hk-91 rifles that were imported from 1974 - 1989.

The bore and chamber are mirror-bright and in excellent condition as you'd expect. The muzzle end of the barrel is threaded to accept the flash hider or other accessories (note that the factory flash hider's innovative locking design permits it to be installed / removed by hand and does not require any tools). The bolt carrier and bolt head are 'IB' coded.

The furniture is German Army surplus, taken directly from a G3 service rifle. It matches nicely and looks menacing on this Hk-91! Definitely something that will turn heads if you decide to take this out to the range! If you really want to take this rifle to the next level, the receiver is factory-designed to accept a Hensoldt Wetzlar 4x24 scope and claw mount.

Included with the rifle are three G3 magazines (two of which are unissued, new-in-wrap), an original G3 canvas sling, and an original cover for the flash hider to keep dirt and debris out of the bore when you're trekking across the African savanna.

Asking $2550 shipped for the lot.
